    "summary": "The Artaxiad Kingdom of Armenia (189 BC – 12 AD) was the first unified Armenian kingdom, founded after the collapse of [[event:1041|Seleucid Empire]] power in the region, reaching its greatest extent under Tigranes the Great who briefly created a near-eastern empire stretching from the Caspian to the Mediterranean.\n\nThe kingdom was established by Artaxias I, formerly a Seleucid general, following Rome's defeat of Antiochus III at the [[event:1156|Battle of Magnesia]]. Armenia occupied a strategic position between Rome and Parthia, and successive Armenian rulers maneuvered between these great powers. Tigranes the Great (reigned 95–55 BC) took advantage of the crisis caused by the [[event:1091|Mithridatic Wars]] to expand dramatically, at one point controlling Syria, Phoenicia, Cilicia, Cappadocia, and Mesopotamia in addition to the Armenian heartland. Roman general Lucullus and then [[event:1096|Pompey's Eastern Campaigns]]'s Pompey dismantled this expanded empire and reduced Armenia to a client kingdom, but the kingdom survived as a buffer state between Rome and Parthia until absorbed by Rome in 12 AD.",
